# Commits listed here are ignored by `git blame` when configured:
#   git config blame.ignoreRevsFile .git-blame-ignore-revs
# (GitHub's web blame view picks this file up automatically with no config.)
# Only add commits that are pure mechanical reformatting with zero logic changes.
#
# This repo squash-merges every PR (main is a straight line of "<title> (#N)"
# commits — verified, no individual PR commits survive merge). That means an
# entry here MUST be updated to the actual squash commit's SHA once its PR
# merges, not left pointing at the individual pre-merge commit — the old SHA
# becomes permanently unreachable the moment the PR merges, and both
# scripts/check-patch-coverage.mjs and `git blame` itself silently stop
# recognizing it. This has already happened twice (once from a mid-PR rebase,
# once from squash-merge on the very next merge) — see check-patch-coverage.mjs
# for how a stale entry now degrades (warns, skips just that entry) instead of
# hard-failing every subsequent PR.
#
# One consequence of squash-merge: if a PR bundles a pure reformat together
# with real feature work (as #493 did), the SHA you're forced to list here is
# the whole squashed commit, not just the reformat — meaning genuinely new,
# uncovered lines from that same PR could theoretically also get excused by
# a future PR that touches them. Low practical risk (this repo requires 100%
# patch coverage at merge time, so there's little "new-and-uncovered" content
# left over to accidentally excuse) but worth knowing. The real fix, next
# time: land a pure reformat as its own isolated PR, never bundled with
# anything else, so the squash commit really is pure.

